            {
                "id": "The Cabin_1772006897072",
                "name": "The Cabin",
                "event_type": "Event",
                "pos": [
                    511.4958022811355,
                    -94.69083256207098
                ],
                "markdown": "## The Cabin\n\nThe cabin door hangs crooked on one hinge, swollen wood jammed against a warped frame. Frank puts his shoulder into it and it gives with a wet, reluctant crack \u2014 the sound of something that's been sealed for years finally surrendering.\n\nThe smell hits him first. Not rot, not exactly. Something older than rot. The ghost of tobacco smoke baked into wood. Mildew. River water that soaked into everything and then slowly, over years, evaporated \u2014 leaving behind a mineral tang, like licking a stone.\n\nIt's small. Barely eight feet across. A cot against the far wall, its mattress reduced to a sagging canvas skin over rusted springs. A potbelly stove in the corner, cold as a headstone, its chimney pipe punched through the ceiling at an angle that was never up to code. A shelf above the cot holds a tin cup, a fork with a bent tine, and a Bible \u2014 King James, clothbound, its spine split. Frank opens it. Someone has underlined passages in Genesis with a heavy hand. Chapter 4, verse 9, is circled three times:\n\n***\"And the LORD said unto Cain, Where is Abel thy brother? And he said, I know not: Am I my brother's keeper?\"***\n\nFrank sets the Bible down carefully.\n\nThere's a table built into the wall beneath a porthole so fogged it barely lets in light. On it:\n\n- **More journal pages**, loose this time, not bound. The same cramped handwriting, but worse \u2014 the letters lurching sideways like a drunk trying to walk a straight line. These entries are different from the logs in the second chest. They're *confessional*. Fragments, mostly. ***\"Didn't mean for it to go that way\"*** appears twice. ***\"The river will keep it\"*** appears three times. And then, near the bottom of the last page, written with what looks like a different pen \u2014 steadier, more deliberate, as if the author sobered up or simply ran out of ways to lie to himself:\n\n  ***\"Jimmy never saw it coming. That's the only mercy I can claim.\"***\n\n- **Scratches on the wall** beside the cot. Not carved \u2014 *gouged*, with something sharp, deep enough to splinter the wood. Tally marks. Frank counts them. Forty-seven. Forty-seven days? Forty-seven nights spent on this boat after whatever happened, happened? Or forty-seven something elses \u2014 drinks, regrets, times this person almost turned themselves in and didn't?\n\n- **A tin box** nailed shut beneath the table. Frank pries it open with his pocketknife. Inside: **a bundle of cash**, old bills, bound with a rubber band that disintegrates at his touch. He doesn't count it. He doesn't need to. It's not a fortune, but it's more than a riverman would carry. Payment. Or a share of something.\n\n- **Scratched into the table surface itself**, in letters large enough to read from the doorway, as if it were meant to be the first thing anyone saw when they entered:\n\n  ***\"GOD FORGIVES. THE RIVER DON'T.\"***\n\nFrank stands in the middle of the cabin and lets the silence settle around him. The boat is a coffin with ambition. Whoever lived here did so as penance \u2014 or as hiding. Maybe both. Maybe, by the end, the distinction didn't matter.\n\nHe thinks about the journal entries. The curated chest. The photograph of two men and a fish and a summer afternoon. The straight razor with its dark hinge.\n\nHe thinks about the word *upstream*, circled twice in the first chest. The map with its heavy X. *The drop.*\n\nHe thinks about the Bible verse. *Am I my brother's keeper?*\n\nJimmy's killer didn't run. That's the thing that settles into Frank's gut like a swallowed stone. Jimmy's killer sat right here, on this cot, in this cabin, on this boat stuck in the mud of a dying river \u2014 and *stayed*.\n\nFrank ducks back through the crooked doorway into the open air. The sky is pale and indifferent above him.\n\nHe's got a key with a strange symbol. A map with an X. A name he can't quite read on a pocket watch. And a dead man's confession written on loose pages in a room that smells like ghosts.\n\nUpstream. Whatever's left of the truth, it's upstream.",
