            {
                "id": "The Third Chest_1772006893664",
                "name": "The Third Chest",
                "event_type": "Event",
                "pos": [
                    512.9961582381123,
                    -260.36823013070136
                ],
                "markdown": "## The Third Chest\n\nThe third chest isn't hidden. That's what bothers Frank.\n\nIt sits in the open, square in the middle of the deck like a table centerpiece, like it was placed there *for* someone. It's newer than the other two \u2014 or at least better cared for. The wood is dark walnut, tongue-and-groove, with brass corner fittings that still catch the light. A chest like this didn't come cheap. A chest like this was *bought* for a purpose.\n\nThere's no lock. No clasp at all. Just a lid resting on its frame, easy as breathing.\n\nFrank lifts it.\n\nInside:\n\n- **A photograph**, cracked along the fold line where someone carried it in a breast pocket for too long. Two men stand on a riverbank, squinting into the sun. One is tall and lean, mid-laugh, a cigarette tucked behind his ear. The other is shorter, thicker through the shoulders, holding up a fish like a trophy. On the back, in pencil: ***\"Me & Jimmy, June. Good times.\"*** The handwriting matches the journal from the second chest.\n- **A straight razor**, folded closed, its bone handle yellowed with age. There's nothing remarkable about it until Frank opens it. The blade is immaculate \u2014 honed, oiled, cared for. Someone maintained this razor long after they stopped using it for shaving. There's a dark stain worked into the hinge that soap and time haven't been able to shift.\n- **A woman's ring**, plain gold band, sized small. No inscription inside, but there's a dent on the outer surface, a deep one, like it was struck against something hard. Or stepped on. Frank rolls it between his thumb and forefinger. It's lighter than it should be \u2014 not solid gold, then. A promise someone couldn't quite afford to keep.\n- **A torn scrap of newspaper**, brittle as dead leaves. Most of the text is gone, but the fragment that remains is from what appears to be a local crime blotter. Frank can make out: ***\"...body recovered downstream near...\"*** and below that, ***\"...no suspects at this...\"*** The date is missing. The name of the deceased is missing. Everything that would make it *useful* is missing. But someone kept it anyway.\n\nFrank stands there, the photograph in one hand, the newspaper scrap in the other.\n\nThe first chest was debris. The second was evidence. This one is something else entirely.\n\nThis is grief.\n\nWhoever packed this box knew Jimmy. Fished with him. Laughed with him. And then \u2014 if the razor and the scrap of newsprint tell the story Frank thinks they're telling \u2014 did something that couldn't be taken back.\n\nHe sets the photograph on top of the chest, face up. The two men grin at him from a summer that's long gone, standing beside a river that no longer exists.\n\n*Good times.*\n\nFrank wonders which one of them is still alive.",
                "stage_notes": "",
                "selected_characters": [],
