            {
                "id": "The Second Chest_1771862206032",
                "name": "The Second Chest",
                "event_type": "Event",
                "pos": [
                    519.693568124551,
                    -390.4183771778039
                ],
                "markdown": "## The Second Chest\n\nThe second chest is smaller than the first \u2014 more of a strongbox, really, shoved beneath a warped bench near the stern. Unlike its companion, this one isn't rusted shut. It's *unlocked*. The clasp hangs open like a mouth mid-sentence, as if whoever left it behind wanted it found.\n\nOr left in a hurry.\n\nFrank lifts the lid. The hinges don't protest. Someone oiled them, and not that long ago \u2014 certainly long after this river stopped running.\n\nInside:\n\n- **A leather-bound journal**, swollen with moisture but still mostly legible. The entries are written in a cramped, hurried hand \u2014 no dates, just numbered passages. Most of it reads like inventory logs: quantities of something measured in *stones* and *barrels*, pickup points along the river. But the last few entries shift in tone. The handwriting gets worse. Shakier. One line, pressed so hard the pen nearly tore the page, reads: ***\"He knows. Jimmy knows.\"***\n- **A brass key**, small and ornate, too delicate for any lock on this boat. It's threaded onto a strip of rawhide like someone wore it around their neck. There's a faint etching on the bow \u2014 a symbol Frank doesn't recognise. A circle with a vertical line through it, bisected by two smaller horizontal strokes.\n- **A hand-drawn map**, rough but deliberate, sketched on the back of what appears to be a bill of sale for lumber. The map shows a stretch of river \u2014 *this* river, Frank is almost sure of it \u2014 with a single location marked upstream by a heavy X. Beside it, in the same cramped handwriting as the journal: ***\"The drop.\"***\n- **A single spent bullet casing**, rolling loose in the corner of the box. .38 caliber. Frank picks it up and turns it in his fingers. It smells like nothing anymore. Whatever story it has to tell, it told it a long time ago.\n\nFrank closes the lid slowly. The first chest held remnants \u2014 leftovers, things forgotten. But this one was *curated*. These items were kept together on purpose.\n\nSomeone wanted a record. Insurance, maybe. Or a confession they never got around to making.\n\nHe looks at the journal entry again. *He knows. Jimmy knows.*\n\nKnew. Jimmy *knew*.",
